definition.value: A medium-chain fatty acid that is the 3-hydroxylated derivative of lauric acid;  associated with fatty acid metabolic disorders.
A cyclohexenecarboxylate that is the conjugate base of shikimic acid.
The (S)-enantiomer of 3-hydroxylauric acid.
A monohydroxy fatty acid with a lauric acid core substituted at position 2 by a hydroxy group, which confers chirality; a component of cellular lipids in Pseudomonas strains.
The (R)-enantiomer of 2-hydroxylauric acid.
The (S)-enantiomer of 2-hydroxylauric acid.
A hydroxy fatty acid comprising lauric acid carrying a hydroxy group at C-4.
An optically active form of 4-hydroxylauric acid having (S)-configuration.
An optically active form of 4-hydroxylauric acid having (R)-configuration.
A cellobiose with beta configuration at the reducing-end glucose residue.
The beta-anomer of lactose.
The alpha-anomer of lactose.
A glycosylgalactose comprising two galactose units joined via an beta-(1->4) linkage.
A beta-D-galactopyranosyl-(1->4)-D-galactopyranose in which the carbon bearing the anomeric hydroxy group has alpha- configuration.
A glycosylglucose consisting of galactose and glucose units linked through a 1-6 glycosidic linkage.
The beta-stereoisomer of allolactose.
The alpha-stereoisomer of allolactose.
Any icosatetraenoic acid with the double bonds at positions 5, 7, 11 and 14.
A compound in which two monosaccharides are joined by a glycosidic bond.
Conjugate base of chenodeoxycholic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid acid that consists of cholane having a carboxy group in place of the methyl group at position 24.
A cholanic acid having 5alpha-configuration.
A trihydroxy-5beta-cholanic acid that is 5beta-cholan-24-oic acid substituted by hydroxy groups at positions  3, 7 and 12 (the 3alpha,7alpha,12beta stereoisomer).
A dihydroxybenzoate having the two hydroxy groups located at the 3- and 4-positions.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 3-(4-hydroxyphenyl)pyruvic acid.
Any carboxylic ester where the carboxylic acid component is  propionic acid.
A monoester of a dicarboxylic acid.
Members of the class of cholanic acids based on a 5beta-cholane skeleton.

Any bile acid conjugated to a functional group that gives additional hydrophilicity or charge to the molecule. Molecules used for conjugation are: glycine, taurine (and other amino acids); sulfuric acid (for which the term ''sulfate'' may be used); glucuronic acid (for which the term ''glucuronate'' may be used); glucose and other uncharged sugars; and coenzyme A.
A N-acylglycinate that is the conjugate base of glycochenodeoxycholic acid.
A but-2-enoic acid having a cis- double bond at C-2.
A but-2-enoate having a cis- double bond at C-2.
Amide of a bile acid with glycine.
An organosulfonate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of taurocholic acid.
The conjugate base of but-2-enoic acid.
The bile acid taurine conjugate of lithocholic acid.
An organosulfonate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of taurodeoxycholic acid.
A monovalent inorganic anion that consists of molybdic acid where one of the two OH groups has been deprotonated.
